<TITLE> Students return to dormitories </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sept 8 (bdnews24.com)  Noakhali Science and Technology University resumed classes Saturday following a government decision Thursday to allow colleges and universities to reopen following a 16-day closure due to the student protests. The university opened its dormitories to students Friday after a decision by its governing body. Other universities across the country are now following their lead. All 26 universities in the country were closed on Aug 23 in the wake of widespread student unrest, triggered by an incident at Dhaka University. Classes were also suspended in the divisional city colleges as well as some colleges in district towns. Education adviser Ayub Quaderi held a meeting with the vice chancellors of all 26 universities on Sept 3. Following the meeting he said: "The vice-chancellors have been advised to make their own decisions on whether to open the universities in consideration of their internal situation." bdnews24.com's Jahangirnagar University correspondent said: "An emergency syndicate meeting Saturday, presided over by vice chancellor Professor Mostahidur Rahman, decided to resume classes Wednesday. On Tuesday 11 halls will reopen." Bangladesh University of Engineering and Technology, Shahjalal University of Science and Technology in Sylhet and Khulna University of Engineering and Technology open Sunday. Sher-e-Bangla Agricultural University in Dhaka will open its student halls on Sept 12. bdnews24
